			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-767045">
				
				<li class="comment-author"   >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                
<img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/22/arbeyu/cb4ba5ac-6522-4ed8-afe6-1cc86365c28c/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/arbeyu" title="User profile page">arbeyu</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">5 March 2007 9:11AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>heike...</p><p>I'm another person without mobile phone, and I do just fine. In fact, it's a positive advantage...</p><p>When I agree to meet somebody, say at a pub, then I can reasonably expect them to meet me there, at the planned time. I don't get text messages saying that the person I'm meeting will be late, or perhaps cannot be arsed coming at all.</p><p>I'm the "I.T. guy" for a medium-sized company, and I know that work would like to be getting in touch with me (usually so that I can tell them to "switch it off and on again") when I'm on my holidays: They can't.</p><p>I don't annoy people by talking loudly into a mobile on a bus or train, or by walking very slowly down the street, weaving from side to side, blocking those behind me as I try to read text messages.</p><p>I don't suffer from that Pavolvian response that most people do to their mobile phone announcing that they have a text message (what's that all about? the whole point about text messages is that YOU DON'T HAVE TO READ THEM RIGHT THERE AND THEN!).</p><p>If I don't want to be contactable, I don't have to justify myself to irate friends who ask "if you've got a mobile phone, why to you bloody well keep switching it off?"</p><p>I honestly believe that my life is more tranquil without a mobile phone than it would be if I had one.</p><p>Until very recently we ALL managed quite well without mobiles. It involved a bit of forward planning ("meet you at my place at eight"), and a bit of contingency planning ("if I'm not in, I'll be in the pub on the corner") but what's the problem with that?</p><p>Ditch your mobile! Free yourself!
</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
